# Project Architecture & Code Organization Directives

This repo follows a **feature-first architecture** with a **shared UI system** and **shared domain modules** (pure functions/types) where appropriate.

Cursor MUST follow the directives below when generating, refactoring, or moving code.

---

## 0. Non-Negotiables (Quality Bar)

Before considering work “done”, Cursor MUST ensure:

- ✅ TypeScript passes
- ✅ Lint passes (if configured)
- ✅ `yarn build` passes

If a change introduces new exports or moves files, Cursor MUST also update any relevant `index.ts` barrel exports.

---

## 1. Primary Layers

### 1.1 Features (`src/features/*`)
**Features own product behavior** (screens, orchestration, data-fetch, mutations, state, composition).

Features MAY:
- Call API clients / hooks
- Compose view components
- Import shared UI from `src/ui`
- Import shared pure utilities/types from `src/shared` (or equivalent)
- Import legacy catalog data from `src/data` ONLY when needed

Features MUST NOT:
- Duplicate shared UI components if one already exists
- Reimplement permission/auth gating ad hoc
- Define large cross-feature design patterns inside a single feature (promote to `src/ui`)

---

### 1.2 Shared UI System (`src/ui/*`)
`src/ui` is the **single source of truth** for reusable UI building blocks.

Cursor MUST:
- Prefer existing `src/ui` components over rolling new buttons/fields/cards/modals
- Add to `src/ui` when a component is reusable across 2+ features
- Keep UI components mostly “dumb”: presentation + small UI logic only

`src/ui` MUST NOT:
- Contain business rules or feature-specific workflows
- Fetch data
- Encode permission decisions (UI can accept `canEdit` booleans / callbacks, but rules live elsewhere)

MUI mapping examples:
- Alert -> ui/primitives/AppAlert
- Chip -> ui/primitives/AppBadge -> ui/patterns/status/*

---

### 1.3 Shared “Domain Modules” (Pure Logic + Types)
This project no longer uses `src/domain`.

Pure, reusable logic SHOULD live in one of:
- `src/shared/**` (recommended)
- `src/lib/**` (if that’s your existing convention)
- `src/features/<feature>/domain/**` (if the logic is feature-scoped but still pure)

Rules for “domain modules”:
- MUST be framework-agnostic (no React, no hooks)
- MUST be deterministic and side-effect free
- MUST accept explicit inputs and return explicit outputs
- SHOULD be unit-testable without mocking browser APIs

Examples:
- stat resolution, game math, visibility/capability helpers
- content patch builders / normalizers
- data shaping that is not UI-specific

---

## 2. Auth & Permission Practices (Mandatory)

### 2.1 Edit gating is required
Any UI that allows changes (edit buttons, inline editable fields, admin menus, destructive actions) MUST be gated.

Gating applies to:
- Edit buttons
- “Add” / “Remove” / “Delete” actions
- Inline editable fields
- Form routes/pages intended only for privileged users
- Mutation triggers inside menus or kebabs

### 2.2 Single-source permission checks
Cursor MUST NOT invent one-off permission logic in components.

Instead:
- Use existing capability helpers (e.g. `canEditX(viewer, resource)`), or
- Add a pure helper in `src/shared/auth/**` or `src/shared/capabilities/**`

UI should consume booleans like:
- `const canEdit = canEditCharacter(ctx, character);`
…and then pass `canEdit` down.

### 2.3 Defense in depth
Even when UI is gated, server/API enforcement is assumed.

Client responsibilities:
- Hide/disable edit UI for unauthorized users
- Avoid firing mutations when unauthorized
- Prefer showing a disabled state + tooltip or simply hiding, following existing patterns

---

## 3. Routes, Views, Hooks (Extraction Rules)

### 3.1 Route components (`*Route.tsx`)
Routes are orchestration only.

Routes MAY:
- Read params
- Run auth hooks/guards
- Compose feature hooks
- Handle loading/error boundaries
- Render a single feature view

Routes MUST NOT:
- Contain complex mutation logic
- Contain long multi-section JSX
- Contain business rules

Extraction triggers (MUST extract):
- Route > ~150 lines OR
- > 1 data-fetching effect OR
- > 3 mutation handlers OR
- > 3 major UI sections

### 3.2 Feature Views (`src/features/<feature>/*View.tsx`)
Feature views render the page layout.

Views:
- MAY import `src/ui` components
- MUST be declarative
- MUST NOT fetch data (receive props from hooks/routes)
- MUST NOT contain business rules (compute booleans via shared helpers upstream)

### 3.3 Feature hooks
If orchestration becomes complex, create:
- `use<Feature>()` for state/data/mutations
- smaller hooks for sub-workflows

---

## 4. Content Model (Schema vs Content) + Patching

This project uses two related concepts:

### 4.1 Component Schema (definition)
- Describes what a component *is* (fields, types, defaults, allowed children, etc.)
- Treated as configuration and is relatively stable

### 4.2 Component Content (instance)
- A specific instance placed on a page/campaign/entity
- Contains actual values for schema-defined fields
- Often nested (parent → children)

### 4.3 Patching strategy
Edits SHOULD be performed via **patch objects** (partial updates), not full rewrites.

Cursor MUST:
- Prefer building minimal patches (only changed fields)
- Preserve unknown fields (do not destructure and drop)
- Avoid overwriting children arrays unless intentionally changing structure
- Maintain stable identifiers for existing nodes (no “regen ids” during edits)

If a helper exists for patch building/merging, Cursor MUST use it.
If not, add a pure helper in `src/shared/content/**` (not inside UI components).

---

## 5. `src/data` is Legacy (Migration in progress)

`src/data` is actively being migrated.

Rules:
- Cursor MUST NOT add new datasets or expand catalogs in `src/data` unless explicitly instructed
- Cursor MAY reference `src/data` when needed for current behavior
- When refactoring, prefer moving logic out of `src/data` into:
  - `src/shared/**` for pure logic
  - `src/features/**` for orchestration
  - `src/ui/**` for reusable UI

---

## 6. Types: Extend, Don’t Redefine (Mandatory)

Cursor MUST:
- Import and extend existing types instead of re-declaring similar shapes
- Prefer `type X = Existing & { ... }` or `interface X extends Existing { ... }`
- Avoid duplicating unions/enums when they already exist

Examples (preferred):
- `type CharacterWithComputed = Character & { computed: ComputedStats }`
- `interface EditWealthPayload extends Wealth { reason?: string }`

Avoid:
- Recreating `Wealth`, `ViewerContext`, `CampaignRole`, etc. in new files
- “Near-duplicate” local types that drift over time

If a type is missing a field:
- Extend it locally if it’s view-specific
- Otherwise, update the source type definition in the canonical types file

---

## 7. Naming & File Hygiene

Prefer intent-based names:
- `capabilities.ts`, `patchBuilder.ts`, `normalizeContent.ts`

Avoid:
- `utils.ts`, `helpers.ts`, `misc.ts` (unless a folder convention already exists)

One concept per file when possible.

---

## 8. When Unsure

If responsibility is ambiguous:
- Default to feature-local placement first
- Promote to `src/ui` only if clearly reusable
- Promote to `src/shared` only if clearly pure and cross-feature

Do NOT invent new architectural layers without instruction.